Focaccia Baladi
  --Ham El-Waylly

350g (scant 3 c) ap flour
200g (1 2/3c) whole wheat bread flour
15g (1 tbsp) evoo
15g (4 1/2 tsp) kosher salt
8g (scant 2 1/2 tsp) instant yeast
630g water (2 2/3 c), room temperature
160g (2/3 c) evoo, divided
55g (1/4 c) wheat germ, divided
Flaky salt

Combine the flours, olive oil, salt, yeast, and water in a large container with a tight-fitting lid, or in a large bowl. Stir with a spatula until no dry spots of flour remain. Cover the container with the lid or bowl with plastic wrap and let sit for 20 min. After 20 min, uncover the dough. Rub some olive oil on your fingers and place them underneath one corner of the dough. Lift and pull the dough to the opposite corner. Repeat with all 4 corners. Repeat the process with all 4 corners one more time. Cover the dough again and let sit for 20 min. Repeat this process (folding all the corners twice every 20 min) 3 more times for a total 5 complete rounds (the total rest time is 1 hr 40 min) Place the dough in the fridge and let sit for 2 whole days. (I know, I’m sorry. Come on this focaccia journey with me.) Pour 1/3 c of the olive oil into a 9x13" metal baking pan and swirl to coat; making sure to get all of the edges. Sprinkle 2 tbsp of the wheat germ along the bottom of the pan and slide the cold dough on top. Press the dough down and outwards with stiff fingertips to fill the pan as much as possible. (There may be some empty corners.) Cover the pan with a towel and leave it in a warm place to proof until it is slightly poofy and has filled the pan, 1-1 1/2 h) Preheat the oven to 500F. Use stiff fingers to press into the dough, creating uniform dimples across the surface. Top with the remaining olive oil and wheat germ. Season with a sprinkle of flaky salt. Bake the focaccia until the top is deeply golden brown, charred in spots, and crunchy all along the base, ~30 min. Transfer to a wire rack to rest for 20 min before slicing and serving.

Pro tip: double recipe and keep some focaccia in the freezer wrapped in plastic wrap and stored in a resealable freezer bag for up to 1 month. Reheat in a 350F oven until warm in the center.

